[2] Cholera - Namibia (Ohangwena)
Date: Fri 14 March 2008
Source: AllAfrica, New Era (Windhoek) report [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200803140404.html>


Nine more suspected cholera cases have been reported in the north, bringing
to 137 the number of infected people in a week. Under-secretary in the
Ministry of Health and Social Services, Dr Norbert Foster, yesterday
afternoon [13 Mar 2008] told New Era that the number of suspected cholera
cases increased from 128 on Wednesday [12 Mar 2008) to 137 in one day.

Since the disease broke out last Saturday [8 Mar 2008], 2 deaths have been
recorded. Of the reported cases, 8 have been confirmed as cholera and 14
patients are admitted at Engela State Hospital. Foster says the rise in the
number of suspected cholera cases is expected given the water situation in
the North. The ministry together with stakeholders is, however, trying to
bring the situation under control by intensifying community awareness on
cholera. Water purification sachets have been distributed to communities
but according to Forster, not every community might have been reached yet.
While water purification remains key to preventing the spread of the
disease, Foster says boiling water might not be easy especially among
communities in villages that heavily depend on firewood for energy.

[byline: Petronella Sibeene]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A map of Namibia showing the province of Ohangwena in the north can be
found at <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ohangwena>. It borders the Angolan
province of Cunene, which has had cholera activity as well. - Mod.LL]

******
[3] Diarrhea, fatal - Nigeria (Anambra)
Date: Fri 14 Mar 2008
Source: The Vanguard (Lagos) [edited]
<http://www.vanguardngr.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=4626&Itemid=45>


Following an outbreak of diarrhea 9 children have been reported dead in
Aguata local government area. Acting chairman of the council, Mr Richard
Obi who spoke to newsmen on the outbreak of the endemic disease said the
affected children were between the ages of one and 3 years. 4 of the
children died at a private hospital in Nkpologwu while 5 children died at a
private hospital in Ekwulobia.

Obi said the local government had to quickly rush to the aid of the
hospitals to save further deaths by distributing 50 cartons of ORT [oral
rehydration therapy] to all the health centers in the council area.

Apart from the area of health, Obi said the council had paid its own
counterpart fund of N19, under the EU project for the provision of
boreholes in the local government area, adding that presently, 15 boreholes
were being drilled in 10 selected communities in Aguata.

[byline: Enyim Enyim]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The etiology of this outbreak is not stated but Anambra is located in
southern Nigeria, not far from where outbreaks of cholera in the Delta and
Cross Rivers states have occurred. The states can be found on a map of
Nigeria at <http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/nigeria.pdf>.
- Mod.LL]

